  <static seed="31" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/FractionArithmetic/MultiplyFractions20.pg">
    <statement><p>Multiply: <m>\displaystyle{ \frac{8}{7} \cdot \frac{5}{6} }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="10" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{20}{21}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To multiply two fractions, usually we simply multiply both numerators and both denominators. However, it<rsq/>s easier to reduce fractions before multiplying:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ 
\begin{aligned}[t]
   \frac{8}{7} \cdot \frac{5}{6}
           \amp = \frac{8 \cdot 5}{7 \cdot 6} \\
           \amp = \frac{4 \cdot 5}{7 \cdot 3} \\
           \amp = \frac{20}{21}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The answer to this question is <m>\displaystyle{\frac{20}{21}}</m>.</p>
<p>Note that we divided the first numerator and the second denominator by <m>2</m>.</p>
</solution>
